   "subject": "REST-017: Found the root cause of the COMMITMENT_SCORE_STUCK pulse \u2014 it's not the detector, it's the logger",
   "text": "The YELLOW pulse you've been getting every 2h since 06-12 ('COMMITMENT_SCORE_STUCK / check ict.pipeline for Commitment detector failed') has been pointing at the wrong thing. The CommitmentDetector is fine. The bug is plumbing:\n\n1) The orchestrator computes the real commitment as a post-pass (_compute_commitment), uses commit.label to veto UNCOMMITTED signals, then throws the state away. _log_decisions logs commitment_score=None.\n2) The in-pipeline logger logs commitment_score=_commit_size_mult, but the orchestrator always calls the pipeline with commitment_result=None (by design \u2014 scores don't exist yet), so that value is the constant default 1.0 every time.\n\nEmpirical proof: decisions_2026_06.jsonl = 1774/1797 entries at exactly 1.0, 23 at None, ZERO with the computed value. Per your CLAUDE.md decision_logger pattern, commitment_score is one of the four features Oracle reads to learn \u2014 so it's been a dead/degenerate column. Oracle can't learn anything keyed on commitment. Same silent-data-loss class as a missing update_outcome().\n\nBonus catch: the field is also mislabeled \u2014 _commit_size_mult is the size multiplier (discrete 0/0.5/0.75/1.0), not the 0-1 score. The right thing to log is commit.score.\n\nI did NOT change anything (live decision-logging change = your logged approval, NON-NEGOTIABLE #4). The one-line-ish fix is queued as RQ-REST-018: thread the orchestrator's computed commit.score into log_ict_decision and stop logging the always-1.0 multiplier; also fix the pulse message text. Details in FIND-REST-017-a/b.\n\nHealth: all 4 loops beating tonight (ict_scanner/forex_scan/morning_briefing/oracle_reflection all GREEN) \u2014 the 06-12 outage stays fixed. Only leftover: data/agent/health.json full sweep is frozen at 06-08 (8 days), so its top-level GREEN and the broker-equity lines aren't trustworthy; re-run the sweep on your Mac (needs network). cb_calendar back-extension to 2023 (RQ-REST-016, the unblock for the CB-blackout wiring RQ-REST-015) is still queued for your sign-off. Capacity: weekly ~58k/200k used after this cycle, full buffer left for your session."
  },
